    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of entanglement. He thought it was \"spooky\" because it seemed to defy classical notions of space and time, where information can't travel faster than the speed of light. In other words, if two particles are entangled, measuring the state of one particle instantly affects the state of the other, even if they're separated by vast distances.\n\nThe \"spooky\" part comes from the fact that this effect happens instantaneously, regardless of the distance between the particles. It's as if the information is being transmitted between them faster than the speed of light, which is a fundamental limit imposed by the laws of physics. This seems to contradict our intuitive understanding of space and time, where cause and effect are typically linked by a causal chain.\n\nEinstein's concern was that if entanglement is real, it would imply that the universe is fundamentally non-local, where information can be transmitted instantaneously across vast distances. This idea challenges our classical understanding of space and time, and it's what Einstein called \"spooky\" because it seems to defy our everyday experience of the world.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that entanglement is not",
